         <p rend="indent">
            During the year ending <date when="1915-06-30">June 30th, 1915</date>, <name type="place" subtype="county">Duval County</name>, and <name type="place" subtype="city">City<lb/>
            of Jacksonville</name>, spent $46,393.58 for the care of indigent hospital<lb/>
            patients. If all these cases could have been cared for at the County<lb/>
            hospital, the total expense would have been not over $33,000.00, estima<lb break="no"/>
            ting upon the basis of the expense incurred by the county for care of<lb/>
            cases handled at the county hospital. In other words, if the county<lb/>
            hospital facilities had been adequate to handle all the indigent hospit<lb break="no"/>
            al cases that devolved upon the public during that period, a saving of<lb/>
            at least $13,000.00 of the tax payers' money would have been effected.<lb/>
         </p>
         <p rend="indent">
            Not only was this extra expenditure necessitated by lack of<lb/>
            adequate facilities but the county authorities were prevented from ef<lb break="no"/>
            fecting many economies that might have been possible with a better<lb/>
            equipment, and from furnishing the public the emergency hospital service<lb/>
            that is so urgently needed. In short, the enforced neglect of many de<lb break="no"/>
            serving cases in this county that has resulted in probably preventable<lb/>
            deaths because of the lack of adequate public hospital facilities, is<lb/>
            so disgraceful a matter as to be no longer tolerated by a civilized<lb/>
            community.<lb/>
         </p>
         <p rend="indent">
            To carry a bond issue of $120,000.00 - the amount needed for<lb/>
            the erection and equipment of an up-to-date hospital building of approx<lb break="no"/>
            imately two hundred bed capacity - would necessitate the assessment of<lb/>
            $10,000.00 annually or one-quarter mill on a dollar valuation, for in<lb break="no"/>
            terest and sinking fund, an amount $3,000.00 less than the possible sav<lb break="no"/>
            ing in the indigent hospital expenses incurred within the county last<lb/>
            year. This possible saving would be augmented by the returns from in<lb break="no"/>
            terest on the sinking fund accumulations and by the increased economies<lb/>
            that could be effected if indigent cases, and pay cases at cost, could<lb/>
            be handled in one properly designed and adequately equipped institution.<lb/>
            The expense for caring for indigent patients at St. Luke's hospital last<lb/>
            year was approximately, $2.00 per day's treatment; at the county hospit<lb break="no"/>
            al, approximately, 80 cents per day's treatment.<lb/>
         </p>
